Part 3

By twenty-six, Vikram's name appeared in a business magazine's "Ones to Watch" list.

By twenty-eight, the same magazine dropped the "Watch" and just wrote his name.

By twenty-nine, three years running, a Forbes list carried him too — always somewhere in the lower half, always misspelling Ahuja as Ahluja in at least one edition, which annoyed Pradhan-babu more than it annoyed Vikram.

None of it had happened in the South.

Not one factory, not one office, nothing below the Godavari.

That map stayed blank on purpose — or, more honestly, out of caution nobody had yet forced him past.

---

The government's new liquor policy arrived like most government policies arrive — as a rumor two months before it was a rule, and a crisis the week after.

New licensing slabs.

Higher duty.

A minister who'd never visited a distillery in his life explaining distillery economics on television with great confidence.

Pradhan-babu, now with a second cardigan for winter, aged but unretired, put it plainly.

"Sir, if this policy stands as drafted, we lose the Odisha license by March."

"Then it won't stand as drafted."

"You're going to fight the state government?"

"I'm going to make sure the state government understands what four thousand jobs look like on paper before they sign anything."

It took eleven months, two industry associations, one strategically-timed press conference, and a compromise nobody loved equally.

The license survived.

Vikram didn't celebrate.

He went home, ate dinner alone, and read the fine print of the amended policy twice, the way some men reread a letter from someone they miss.

---

Ira Sen came to interview him for that same press conference.

Business desk, a mid-size paper with ambitions of a bigger one.

She asked sharper questions than the ones from bigger papers.

"Everyone talks about the license survival. Nobody's asking what it cost you personally to fight it."

Nobody had asked him that in eleven months.

"Is that an interview question?"

"No," she said. "That one's for me."

He liked that she said it.

---

The second interview never happened, officially — she came back to "fact-check one quote" and stayed for dinner instead, and neither of them ever filed that particular follow-up story.

She had a way of sitting across a table that made boardrooms feel like a different profession entirely — elbows on the wood, chin low over folded hands, watching him the way she watched a source about to say something he shouldn't.

"You're doing it again," he told her once.

"Doing what?"

"Interviewing me. Off the record."

"Everything's off the record with you until you decide otherwise."

He decided otherwise, slowly, over that autumn.

Their first evening alone lasted until neither of them noticed the driver had circled the block four times waiting for a call that never came.

Streetlight through a car window, her fingers loosely laced through his on the seat between them, the ordinary electricity of two people who had spent months performing restraint and had finally, wordlessly, agreed to stop.

He remembered afterward — for years afterward, longer than he'd admit — the particular warmth of her hand finding the back of his neck, unhurried, like she had all the time reporters never actually have.

The first time he kissed her, it was raining lightly outside her apartment door, and she pulled him in not out of urgency but out of a kind of amused inevitability, as though she'd already written this scene in her head days ago and was simply letting him catch up to the draft.

Her apartment smelled of old newsprint and jasmine agarbatti, an unlikely combination that he came, that winter, to think of as the actual smell of being wanted.

She would trace the pad of her thumb along his collarbone while he was still catching his breath from a day of board pressure he hadn't managed to leave at the office, and ask him nothing — no questions, off record or on — until his shoulders dropped an inch on their own.

That was the thing balance sheets never gave him.

Silence that asked for nothing back.

Some nights it was unhurried — her head against his chest, the city traffic outside dimming to a hum, her voice low and half-laughing about some editor's ridiculous headline choice, his hand slow along her spine, no destination, no deadline, the rarest kind of time a man like him ever got to spend.

Other nights it was faster, hungrier, both of them arriving at each other like the day had cost something and this was the only currency that paid it back — her fingers working his tie loose before either of them had said a single word, his mouth at her throat, the particular urgency of two people who each privately suspected, correctly or not, that this couldn't possibly last and were determined not to waste an hour of it.

He never told Pradhan-babu why he started leaving the office by eight most evenings.

He never told Rohan why he'd started smiling at his phone at odd hours, a habit their father would have found, if he'd lived to see it, both endearing and faintly ridiculous.

He gave her, without her asking twice, a supplementary card on his account — the kind of gesture rich men make when they want love to feel like less of a transaction, and it always, invisibly, becomes one anyway.

---

That October, during Durga Puja week, she told him she had an assignment.

"Delhi. Festive coverage. Three days."

"Take the car to the airport."

"I'll take a cab, don't fuss."

He fussed anyway. Ordered a car for her from the office, driver and all, insisted.

She left for the airport, she said, on the Tuesday.

On Wednesday afternoon, his phone buzzed once — a transaction alert, the bank's dry little message, the kind he usually didn't even read.

*Rs. 340 debited — Café Coffee Day, Salt Lake, near the press building.*

He looked at it twice.

Salt Lake was eleven kilometers from the airport, and considerably farther from Delhi.

He almost called her.

Then thought: flight delayed, she's killing time near office before catching a later one, of course, why panic.

He had, that week, been meaning to give her something.

A car of her own — not office-arranged, hers, cream-colored, ribbon still in the boot because he hadn't decided yet whether that was too much or exactly enough.

He thought: if she's still in the city, let me surprise her before she leaves.

He drove it there himself.

---

The building security let him through without question; his face, by then, opened most doors in that city without needing a name.

Her cabin was on the second floor, glass-walled on one side, the blinds half down.

The door was ajar.

He didn't knock.

He'd never needed to before.

He pushed it open expecting to see her at her desk, phone to her ear, ready to be surprised.

What he saw instead took his mind a full two seconds longer to process than it should have — the kind of two seconds where the body understands before the brain agrees to.

Her blouse, unbuttoned wrong, hung off one shoulder.

A man's belt lay uncoiled on the floor near the desk leg — Rajeev, junior sub-editor, someone Vikram had shaken hands with twice at office parties and forgotten both times.

Underwear — hers, his — scattered without any pretense of having been placed rather than dropped.

Neither of them heard the door.

For one full second, nobody in that room moved.

Vikram didn't shout.

Didn't ask a single question he already had every answer to.

He stepped back.

Closed the door as quietly as he had opened it — quieter, if anything, as though the one courtesy left to give was silence.

---

Downstairs, the cream-colored car sat exactly where the driver had parked it, ribbon still tied in the boot.

Vikram stood beside it for perhaps a minute.

Nobody watching him would have called what came over his face rage.

It looked, if anything, like arithmetic — a man solving one final sum before closing the book.

He picked up a fist-sized stone from the flowerbed lining the entrance.

Didn't swing it in fury.

Brought it down once, deliberately, on the windshield.

Then once more on the bonnet, denting the cream paint he'd chosen himself two weeks ago after looking at eleven color swatches with an attention to detail he never gave his own wardrobe.

He set the stone down on the driver's seat, almost politely, the way you'd return a book you'd borrowed.

Got into his own car.

Left the gift exactly where it stood — wrecked, ribboned, and paid for.

---

Ira came down forty minutes later, adjusting an earring, laughing at something Rajeev had said in the lift.

She stopped at the sight of the car.

Glass across the pavement, catching the streetlight.

The security guard, an older man named Naresh who had opened that gate for Vikram eleven times that year without ever learning his last name, stepped forward.

"Madam.

Vikram sir came.

Brought this car for you.

Left it there.

Then left in anger."

Ira said nothing for a long moment.

Rajeev, beside her, asked what everyone in that story except Vikram always asks too late.

"Did he see us?"

Nobody answered him.

Ira was still looking at the ribbon, soaked now from where the radiator had leaked out beneath the car overnight, still tied in a bow nobody would ever get to undo the way it was meant to be undone.

---

He never spoke her name again.

Not to Pradhan-babu, who never asked.

Not to Rohan, who heard a version of it third-hand years later and never brought it up.

Not, for a long time, to anyone.

The card was cancelled the next morning — a five-minute phone call, no note, no message.

Some silences are just silence.

Others are the loudest thing a man ever says.
